description: The 'works_list' tool returns a list of work items based on specified filters. It supports various arguments such as filtering by part, creator, priority, stage, ownership, ticket status, severity, source channel, and work type. Users can request a maximum number of items to be returned and filter work based on Rev organization associations. This tool provides a comprehensive way to search for and filter work items according to various criteria, helping users to efficiently manage and track their work items.
examples:
query1: List all work items created by user A.
query2: Show work items with priority P1.
query3: Filter work by stage "In Progress".
query4: Return work items with severity "High".
query5: Display work items created through email channel.
query6: Get the latest 10 work items created.
query7: Filter work items associated with Rev organization X.
query8: Show work items with ticket status "Resolved".
query9: List work items related to part number P1234.
query10: Return work items of type "Bug".

arguments.name: applies_to_part
arguments.description: Filters for work belonging to any of the provided parts

arguments.name: created_by
arguments.description: Filters for work created by any of these users

arguments.name: issue_priority
arguments.description: Filters for issues with any of the provided priorities. Allowed values: p0, p1, p2, p3

arguments.name: issue_rev_orgs
arguments.description: Filters for issues with any of the provided Rev organizations

arguments.name: limit
arguments.description: The maximum number of works to return. The default is '50'

arguments.name: owned_by
arguments.description: Filters for work owned by any of these users

arguments.name: stage_name
arguments.description: Filters for records in the provided stage(s) by name

arguments.name: ticket_needs_response
arguments.description: Filters for tickets that need a response

arguments.name: ticket_rev_org
arguments.description: Filters for tickets associated with any of the provided Rev Organizations

arguments.name: ticket_severity
arguments.description: Filters for tickets with any of the provided severities. Allowed values: blocker, high, low, medium

arguments.name: ticket_source_channel
arguments.description: Filters for tickets with any of the provided source channels

arguments.name: type
arguments.description: Filters for work of the provided types. Allowed values: issue, ticket, task

description: The 'summarize_objects' tool is designed to summarize a list of objects. It supports an array of objects as an input argument, allowing for the summarization of various object types. The internal logic for summarizing each object type is handled within the tool's implementation, providing a flexible and adaptable solution for data summarization needs. The tool's purpose is to streamline the process of summarizing diverse sets of objects, without the need for specific use-case customization.

query1: Summarize a list of customer feedback objects using the 'summarize_objects' tool.
query2: Summarize a collection of product review objects using the 'summarize_objects' tool.
query3: Summarize a group of financial data objects using the 'summarize_objects' tool.
query4: Provide a summary of user behavior objects by utilizing the 'summarize_objects' tool.
query5: Summarize a set of employee performance review objects using the 'summarize_objects' tool.
query6: Utilize 'summarize_objects' to condense a series of event data objects into a summarized format.
query7: Generate a summary of medical records objects with the help of the 'summarize_objects' tool.
query8: Summarize a batch of inventory data objects with the assistance of the 'summarize_objects' tool.
query9: Utilize 'summarize_objects' to encapsulate a range of survey response objects into a concise summary.
query10: Summarize a collection of research findings objects using the 'summarize_objects' tool.

description: The 'prioritize_objects' tool sorts a list of objects based on internal priority logic. It takes a list of objects as input and returns a prioritized list. The tool's functionality is not dependent on the specific logic used to determine priority for each object, making it versatile for a wide range of applications.
examples:
query1: Prioritize a list of tasks based on their urgency and importance.
query2: Sort a list of projects based on their potential impact on the company's revenue.

query7: Arrange a list of marketing strategies based on their estimated return on investment.
query8: Sort a list of employee tasks based on their deadline and importance to the company.
query9: Organize a list of customer complaints based on their impact on brand reputation.

description: The add_work_items_to_sprint tool is designed to add specified work items to a sprint. Users can input a list of work item IDs to be included in the sprint, along with the ID of the target sprint. This tool is essential for teams looking to streamline and manage their sprint planning and execution processes effectively.
examples:
- Example 1: From the backlog B, add work items W1, W2, and W3 to sprint S1.
- Example 2: Add work item W4 to sprint S2. 
- Example 3: Include work items W5 and W6 from the pending list to sprint S3. 
- Example 4: Insert work item W7 into sprint S4.
- Example 5: Assign work items W8, W9, and W10 to sprint S5. 
- Example 6: Move work item W11 to sprint S6.
- Example 7: Allocate work items W12 and W13 to sprint S7.
- Example 8: Place work item W14 in sprint S8.
- Example 9: Transfer work items W15 and W16 to sprint S9.
- Example 10: Add work item W17 to sprint S10 and remove work item W18 from it.

arguments.name: work_ids
arguments.description: A list of work item IDs to be added to the sprint.

arguments.name: sprint_id
arguments.description: The ID of the sprint to which the work items should be added

description: The 'get_similar_work_items' tool returns a list of work items that are similar to a given work item. It requires the work item ID as an argument and provides the corresponding list of similar items. This tool is designed to help users identify related work items within a larger set, facilitating efficient organization and analysis of related tasks or projects.
examples:
query1: Get similar work items for work item ID WI-123.
query2: Find related tasks for work item ID WI-456.
query3: Retrieve similar work items for project X.
query4: List work items similar to task T-789.
query5: Show similar tasks for sprint S-23.
query6: Display related work items for user story US-789.
query7: Find similar work items for bug report BR-456.
query8: Get related tasks for feature F-123.
query9: List work items similar to story ST-456.
query10: Show similar tasks for epic EP-789.

arguments.name: work_id
arguments.description: The ID of the work item for which you want to find similar items

description: The 'search_object_by_name' tool takes a search string as input and returns the id of a matching object in the system of record. It is capable of identifying a customer's name, part name, or user name, and provides the id of the best match found. If multiple matches are found, it returns the one with the highest confidence level. This tool is designed to quickly and accurately locate specific objects within the system based on user-defined search criteria.
examples:
Query 1: Find the id of the customer named John Smith.
Query 2: Search for the part named "ABC123" and retrieve its id.
Query 3: Use the tool to identify the user with the username "jsmith" and return their id.
Query 4: I need to locate the id of the customer with the name "Jane Doe".
Query 5: Look up the id of the part with the name "XYZ789".
Query 6: Retrieve the id of the user with the username "jdoe123".
Query 7: Can you provide the id of the customer named "Alex Johnson"?
Query 8: Get the id of the part called "DEF456".
Query 9: What is the id of the user with the username "ajohn"?
Query 10: Locate the id of the customer named "Robert Brown".

arguments.name: query
arguments.description: The search string, could be for example customer’s name, part name, user name.

description: The `create_actionable_tasks_from_text` tool extracts actionable insights from a given text and generates corresponding tasks. These tasks serve as work items and are based on the actionable insights found in the text. The tool takes a single argument - 'text', which is the input text from which actionable insights need to be extracted. This tool facilitates the efficient creation of tasks based on the contents of a text, streamlining the process of addressing actionable items within the text.
examples:
query1: I have the minutes from the last project meeting, can the 'create_actionable_tasks_from_text' tool help extract actionable insights and tasks from it?
query2: Would this tool be able to parse through a customer complaint email to identify and create actionable tasks?
query3: Can I use the 'create_actionable_tasks_from_text' tool to generate tasks from the feedback received from the recent product beta testing?

query5: I need to create actionable tasks from the research findings report, can this tool assist in that process?

query7: Can I input the user feedback survey results into the 'create_actionable_tasks_from_text' tool to create actionable tasks for improvement?

query10: Is it possible to use this tool to extract actionable tasks from the board meeting minutes?
